				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: I'll never get it...<a name="31198"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 28 04 4:08 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I can't read locs or maps very well.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Well, my friend, if you have the ability and desire to learn to use maps, you can, but only if you're prepared to expend some effort.  First thing to do, if you haven't already, is get a printed copy of the zone(s) you're interested in and study it (them).  Next, learn to use the in-game map interface.  Download a complete set of maps from a site such as <a target="_new" href="http://www.mapfiend.net">http://www.mapfiend.net</a>.  Try to download individual, multi-layered maps for the difficult to navigate zones such as unfamiliar dungeons.  Then use the interface--a lot if necessary.
<br />

<br />
The /loc feature is really just a giant Cartesian coordinate system--two axes starting at the origin--point 0,0--north/south, east/west--latitude and longitude.  Nice to know, but really the only time I use it these days is when I need to find a specific point that's not mapped, such as a shouted loot drop.  For general navigation I use the maps.  However, if you wish to learn to use it, go to a familiar zone, make a /loc hotkey--and practice.  Also, don't forget to enable your compass; it's another great tool.
<br />

<br />
The best advice I can give you is take the time and effort to learn to use the maps, unless you want to limit your enjoyment of the game or be guided for the rest of your EQ career.  Now, go find that midget in Sol A and give him what he wants.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
